[[File:Longnon, Auguste Honoré (Pierre Petit, 1899).jpg|right|thumb|Auguste Longnon]] '''Auguste Honoré Longnon''' (18 October 1844, Paris – 12 July 1911, Paris) was a French [[historian]] and [[archivist]]. He is remembered for his research in the field of [[historical geography]] and for his edition of the 15th century poet, [[Francois Villon]].
== Biography == Up to the age of 20 he worked as a shoemaker for his father. From 1868 he studied at the [[École pratique des Hautes Études]] in Paris, and at the same time, worked at the [[Archives nationales (France)|National Archives]] as an assistant to [[Alfred Maury]]. Later on, he received a promotion as ''sous-chef'' at the Archives, and eventually became a director of studies at the École pratique des Hautes Études. From 1892 to 1911 he held the chair of historical geography at the [[Collège de France]].<ref name=MM>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1mXVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=%22Auguste+Longnon%22+%22+Coll%C3%A8ge+de+France%22+1892&source=bl&ots=Htz4BNJ8G2&sig=jYEMsdVLjWV0sMVqpOeWNqTYtOQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGm_XD653KAhXJ8z4KHbXbCQ0Q6AEINjAD#v=onepage&q=%22Auguste%20Longnon%22%20%22%20Coll%C3%A8ge%20de%20France%22%201892&f=false The Medieval Way of War: Studies in Medieval Military History] edited by Gregory I. Halfond</ref> In 1886, he was chosen as a member of the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]].<ref>[http://www.aibl.fr/membres/academiciens-depuis-1663/ Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres] list of members</ref>
== Published works == In the 1880s he published an atlas of French history, "''Atlas historique de la France depuis César jusqu'à nos jours''", that is considered to constitute the actual beginning of French [[historical atlas]]es.<ref name=MM/> The following is a listing of some of Longnon's many original works and editions of other authors: * ''Études sur les pagi de la Gaule'', 1869 &ndash; Studies on the [[pagus|pagi]] of [[Gaul]]. * ''François Villon et ses légataires'', 1873 &ndash; Francois Villon and his legatees. * ''Géographie historique et administrative de la Gaule romaine'', 1876-93 (with [[Ernest Desjardins]]) &ndash; Historical and administrative geography of [[Roman Gaul]]. * ''Étude biographique sur François Villon, d'après les documents inédits conservés aux archives nationales'', 1877 &ndash; Biographical study of François Villon, according to unpublished documents held by the National Archives. * ''Géographie de la Gaule au VIe siècle'', 1878 &ndash; Geography of Gaul in the 6th century. * ''Atlas historique de la France depuis César jusqu'à nos jours'', 1885-89 &ndash; Historical atlas of France from the time of Caesar up to the present. * ''Dictionnaire topographique du département de la Marne'', 1891 &ndash; Topographical dictionary of the [[Marne (departement)|département of Marne]]. * ''Œuvres complètes de François Villon, publiées d'après les manuscrits et les plus anciennes éditions'', 1892 &ndash; Complete works of François Villon. * ''Méliador. Roman comprenant les poésies lyriques de Wenceslas de Bohême, duc de Luxembourg et de Brabant'', (main author: [[Jean Froissart]], published for the first time by Longnon) 1895-99 &ndash; "Meliador". Including lyrical poems of [[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Luxembourg|Wenceslas of Bohemia, duke of Luxembourg and of Brabant]]. * ''Origine des noms de communes du département de la Haute-Marne'', 1908 &ndash; The origin of commune names in the department of [[Haute-Marne]]. * ''Origines & formation de la nationalité française; éléments ethniques--unité territoriale'', 1912 &ndash; Origins and formation of French national identity; ethnic elements, territorial units. * ''Les noms de lieu de la France; leur origine, leur signification, leurs transformations'', issued in 5 parts; 1920-29 (other authors: Léon Mirot, Paul Georges François Joseph Marichal) &ndash; Place names of France, their origins, meanings, transformations.<ref>[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Search/Home?lookfor=%22Longnon,Auguste,1844-1911.%22&type=author&inst= HathiTrust Digital Library] published works</ref>
