'''Espeland Falls'''<ref>''General Studies Paper I for Civil Services Preliminary Examinations''. 2015. New Delhi: McGraw Hill, p. 60.</ref><ref>Braekstad, H. L. 1896. The Right Way to See Norway. ''The English Illustrated Magazine'', p. 467.</ref><ref>[http://www.janus.no/en/om-janus-2/historikk1jr Janus: The history of Janus.]</ref> ({{lang-no|Espelandsfossen}}) is a {{convert|75|m|adj=on}} tall [[waterfall]] located in the Espeland Valley<ref>Langåker, Margrete Øie. 2014. ''Joberget Tunnel – Analysis of Stability and Support Design for Tunneling in Soil''.  Trondheim: Norwegian University of Science and Technology, Department of Geology and Mineral Resources Engineering, p. 8.</ref> ({{lang-no|Espelandsdalen}}) in the municipality of [[Granvin]] in [[Hordaland]] county, [[Norway]].  The falls are located just above large Lake Espeland<ref>Gullick, C. F. W. R., & E. A. Aste. 1943. ''Norway'', vol. 2. London: Naval Intelligence Division, p. 204.</ref><ref>Thomas Cook Ltd. 1901. ''Cook's Handbook to Norway: With the Principal Routes to Sweden and Denmark''. London: T. Cook & Son, p. 73.</ref> ({{lang-no|Espelandsvatnet}}), near the border of Granvin and neighboring municipality of [[Ulvik]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Espelandsfossen-490/|title=World Waterfall Database|accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>

Due to an [[urban legend]], Espeland Falls is sometimes erroneously claimed to be {{convert|2307|ft}} tall.  One theory is that the erroneous information may have originated from a misunderstanding of the concept [[Meters of Head]] in relation to the development of the [[Espeland River]] ({{lang-no|Espelandselvi}}) for [[hydropower]]. Another theory is that there may have been a mixup with ''[[Skrikjofossen]]'' in [[Lofthus, Hordaland|Lofthus]], [[Ullensvang]], a 455 m waterfall located about 60&nbsp;km south of Espeland Falls.

