'''Wilbur Zelinsky''' (December 21, 1921<ref>[http://geogweb.berkeley.edu/PeopleHistory/History/60YrsGeog/Zelinsky,%20Wilbur.html Listing from Geography at Berkeley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419014218/http://geogweb.berkeley.edu/PeopleHistory/History/60YrsGeog/Zelinsky,%20Wilbur.html |date=19 April 2012 }}</ref> – May 4, 2013<ref>[http://www.geog.psu.edu/zelinsky-memorial] Notice of death on Department of Geography website, Pennsylvania State University</ref>) was an American [[Cultural geography|cultural geographer]].<ref name="Mitchell2000">{{cite book|last=Mitchell|first=Don|title=Cultural geography: a critical introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SKlasNjUFNgC&pg=PA29&dq=%22Walter+Zelinsky%22&hl=en&ei=M1FlTLHIGoL6lwen95GTDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Walter%20Zelinsky%22&f=false|accessdate=13 August 2010|year=2000|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=9781557868923|pages=29–33}}</ref> He was most recently a professor [[emeritus]] at [[Pennsylvania State University]]. He also created the [[Zelinsky Model|Zelinsky Model of Demographic Transition]].
==Background and education== An [[Illinois]]an by birth, but a "northeasterner by choice and conviction", Zelinsky received his education at [[University of California, Berkeley]], where he was a student of [[Carl Sauer]]. He received his doctorate in 1953.
==Scholarship== Zelinsky made numerous geographical studies of American popular culture, ranging from the diffusion of classical place-names to spatial patterns of personal given names and to the spatial patterning of religious denominations. One of his most ambitious and imaginative projects was a provocative assessment of the impact of increasingly powerful personal preference on the spatial character of American society.
During the 1960s, along with Gordon DeJong, Warren Robinson, and Paul Baker, Zelinsky helped launch a population research center and coordinate an interdisciplinary graduate instructional program in population studies at Penn State and thus helped lay the foundation for what would become the dual-title [http://www.pop.psu.edu/demography Graduate Program in Demography]. During 1972–1973 Zelinsky served as the first Director of the Population Issues Research Center (what would become the [http://www.pop.psu.edu Population Research Institute] at Penn State).<ref>Population Research Institute website http://www.pop.psu.edu/news/2013/zelinsky</ref>
In 1973, Zelinsky published ''The Cultural Geography of the United States''. In addition to his research in popular culture, Zelinsky made substantial contributions in the fields of "population" and "folk geography".
==Recognition== * Award for Meritorious Contributions to the Field of Geography, presented by the [[Association of American Geographers]] (1996). * The [[Cullum Geographical Medal]] by the [[American Geographical Society]] in 2001. * President of the [[Association of American Geographers|AAG]] from 1972 to 1973.
